Semantic Versioning Strategy
=============================

This template uses Semantic Versioning (https://semver.org/) with automatic patch version incrementing.

Format: vMAJOR.MINOR.PATCH
Example: v1.0.0 → v1.0.1 → v1.0.2 → v1.1.0 → v2.0.0

Versioning Rules
----------------

PATCH (v1.0.0 → v1.0.1):
- Incremented AUTOMATICALLY on each merge to main
- Represents bug fixes, minor improvements, or template fixes
- CI/CD creates tag automatically

MINOR (v1.0.0 → v1.1.0):
- Incremented MANUALLY when adding new features/functionality
- Represents new stories completed or feature additions
- Tag created manually: git tag v1.1.0 && git push origin v1.1.0

MAJOR (v1.0.0 → v2.0.0):
- Incremented MANUALLY for breaking changes
- Represents significant architectural changes
- Tag created manually: git tag v2.0.0 && git push origin v2.0.0

Automatic Tagging
-----------------

The GitHub Actions CI/CD workflow (.github/workflows/ci.yml) automatically:
1. Triggers on merge to main
2. Runs full template verification (scaffold → AIOX → tests → acceptance)
3. On success, reads the latest git tag
4. Increments PATCH version
5. Creates new tag (e.g., v1.0.0 → v1.0.1)
6. Pushes tag to remote

View all tags: git tag -l
View tag info: git show v1.0.0
Delete local tag: git tag -d v1.0.0
Delete remote tag: git push origin --delete v1.0.0

Release Timeline
----------------

- v1.0.0-v1.0.x: Phase 1 - AIOX Integration (Stories 1.1-1.4)
- v1.1.0+: Phase 2 - Application Development (Stories 1.5+)
- v2.0.0: Major release with breaking changes (if applicable)
